<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" box="[199,555,222,249]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,382,222,249]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Common name</emphasis>
. Striped nerite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,259,285]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Morphology</emphasis>
. Medium-sized species. Oval shaped shell has dimensions up to 
<quantity box="[1093,1176,259,285]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
. Colouration pattern is greyish or yellowish-grey with three distinct dark transversal stripes. Occasionally colouration can be uniformly brown, or black. Operculum is reddish and resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[759,895,331,357]" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cycloneritimorpha" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fluviatilis">
<emphasis box="[759,775,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[789,895,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">fluviatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it lacks enlarged apophysal plate. For more details see 
<bibRefCitation author="Gloer, P." box="[274,455,366,393]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refId="ref47000" refString="Gloer, P. (2019) The freshwater gastropods of the West-Palaearctis. Biodiversity Research Laboratory, Hetlingen, 399 pp." type="book" year="2019">Glöer (2019: 53</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 43).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,496,402,429]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. The striped nerite has mostly a Danuban distribution (
<bibRefCitation author="Solymos, P. &amp; Feher, Z." box="[1123,1393,403,429]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="9314252" refId="ref57009" refString="Solymos, P. &amp; Feher, Z. (2011) Theodoxus transversalis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2011, e. T 21726 A 9314252. [downloaded 24 March 2021] https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2011 - 2. RLTS. T 21726 A 9314252. en" type="journal article" year="2011">Sólymos &amp; Fehér 2011</bibRefCitation>
). In the past it was more common in the larger rivers of central Europe, including the Danube itself (
<bibRefCitation author="Feher, Z. &amp; Albrecht, C. &amp; Sereda, S. &amp; Krizsik, V." box="[1228,1425,439,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="300 - 307" refId="ref46132" refString="Feher, Z., Albrecht, C., Sereda, S. &amp; Krizsik, V. (2012) Extremely low genetic diversity in the endangered striped nerite, Theodoxus transversalis (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Neritidae) - a result of ancestral or recent effects? North-western Journal of Zoology, 8 (2), 300 - 307." type="journal article" year="2012">
Fehér 
<emphasis box="[1301,1350,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Reminders of its wider distribution range are a few isolated recent populations, viz., populations from the Dojran Lake (southern Balkan; Fischer 
<emphasis box="[517,568,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">et al</emphasis>
. 2009), and from the Crete Island (Aegean Sea; Szerkowski, 1998). Similar to other species of the genus, it prefers hard substrate (rock, vegetation, man-made materials etc.). Smaller watercourses, and tributaries of the Danube River are considered as its main habitats in 
<collectingCountry box="[1091,1163,583,609]" name="Serbia" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Serbia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Markovic, V. &amp; Tomovic, J. &amp; Ilic, M. &amp; Kracun-Kolarevic, M. &amp; Novakovic, B. &amp; Paunovic, M. &amp; Nikolic, V." box="[1179,1425,583,609]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="477 - 484" refId="ref51007" refString="Markovic, V., Tomovic, J., Ilic, M., Kracun-Kolarevic, M., Novakovic, B., Paunovic, M. &amp; Nikolic, V. (2014) Distribution of the species of Theodoxus Montfort, 1810 (Gastropoda: Neritidae) in Serbia: an Overview. Acta Zoologica Bulgarica, 66 (4), 477 - 484." type="journal article" year="2014">
Marković 
<emphasis box="[1298,1356,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Stable populations have been recorded in the Velika Morava and Nišava Rivers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,378,654,681]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Other remarks</emphasis>
. Relict species of the genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Bunje, P. M. &amp; Lindberg, D. R." box="[703,977,655,681]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="373 - 387" refId="ref44291" refString="Bunje, P. M. &amp; Lindberg, D. R. (2007) Lineage divergence of a freshwater snail clade associated with post-Tethys marine basin development. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 42 (2), 373 - 387. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.06.026" type="journal article" year="2007">Bunje &amp; Lindberg 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Due to decreasing population trend, the species is considered as EN on the IUCN list (
<bibRefCitation author="Solymos, P. &amp; Feher, Z." box="[669,935,691,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="9314252" refId="ref57009" refString="Solymos, P. &amp; Feher, Z. (2011) Theodoxus transversalis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2011, e. T 21726 A 9314252. [downloaded 24 March 2021] https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2011 - 2. RLTS. T 21726 A 9314252. en" type="journal article" year="2011">Sólymos &amp; Fehér 2011</bibRefCitation>
). This snail is listed in the 92/43 EEC Direc- tive (annexes II and IV; 
<bibRefCitation author="Directive, H." box="[422,600,727,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="7 - 50" refId="ref45217" refString="Directive, H. (1992) Council Directive 92 / 43 / EEC of 21 May 1992 on the conservation of natural habitats and of wild fauna and flora. Official Journal of the European Union, 206, 7 - 50." type="journal article" year="1992">Directive, 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
